------------------------------------------------------------<br>
<br>
Monday, November 26th 2001 9:48 PM EST <br>
Deep Thoughts <br>
Posted by Waylander <br>
Earlier this month, I posted a <br>
DAOC vs Shadowbane - Review where I discussed some of the things that DAOC had implemented which also happened to be similiar in concept to things that Shadowbane planned to implement.<br>
<br>
Many of the guilds planning to go to Shadowbane went to DAOC to get used to largeGroup vs Group combat. Before commmitting 50 bucks for the game and 12 bucks a month, most of these guilds read up on the game features or had people in its beta before spending the money for it.<br>
<br>
Now, less than 45 days after the retail launch many guilds are crying foul and throwing in the towel or their ingame active memberships are dwindling. More concerning is that some of the guilds doing this were DAOC fanboy guilds that wouldn't have given Shadowbane a second thought but are now considering it as an option.<br>
<br>
Important decision makers for what veteran guilds do often falls in the hands of the guildmaster or ruling council for a guild. Usually when those people label a game as &quot;sux&quot; or whatnot, then 90% of the guild accounts tend to get cancelled shortly after that and their money goes to support a new game or a former game. People play games to be around their friends, and they generally migrate to where ever their friends are playing.<br>
<br>
Things that turn guilds OFF <br>
<br>
A game that is released, not completed, and the company opts to patch in content/fixes/etc over the life of the game.<br>
<br>
A game where you have to be level &quot;X&quot; or be owned like a 5 dolla hoe.<br>
<br>
A game where patches tweak/nerf/enhance character classes after retail AND the inability for players to adjust without rerolling. Once you mess with just 1 class, you enrage the masses who spam boards claiming they are now nerfed or class &quot;X&quot; is now superpowered.<br>
<br>
A game where it takes more than 1 gaming night(3 hour session) to reach the next level or achieve some type of tangible advancement. <br>
<br>
A gaming environment that does not have enough content to support the player base and their leveling/loot/cash needs.<br>
<br>
A game where PVE balance is fine, but PvP balance is out of whack. Note: no game since UO has gotten this right<br>
<br>
A game where you can no longer group with friends because you are too low level to contribute to the group and are just an xp leech. <br>
<br>
A game where group PvP is important, takes much time and effort to coordinate, and typically ends in under 2 minutes. <br>
<br>
A game that revolves around PvP, but does not allow gamers a mechanisim to quickly reach a hard/soft cap and enjoy Post Max gaming without forcing you through a long and tedious leveling treadmill. <br>
<br>
A game where you spend enormous amounts of wasted time running around the land for routine travel, hunting, etc.<br>
<br>
A game where a guild has no impact on the game world, and where wars are meaningless regardless of who wins.<br>
<br>
Stick to the focus of the game <br>
<br>
Shadowbane is Guild Vs Guild / Empire Vs Empire<br>
<br>
DAOC is Guild vs Guild / Realm vs Realm<br>
<br>
This is the meat and bones of these two games. Guilds are playing for these reasons and the glory they can bring.<br>
<br>
In a game where conflict is promoted, there must be a few elements:<br>
<br>
1. It must have meaning or incentives to make war<br>
<br>
2. There must be consequences for loss<br>
<br>
3. You shouldn't have to be &quot;X&quot; level to be involved<br>
<br>
4. Combat should involve more than just who has the most numbers and highest levels. <br>
<br>
5. Combat should not take hours to organize and move to the battlefield only to win or lose in 2 minutes. <br>
<br>
6. There should be resources to fight over, and a real impact for a victory or a loss.<br>
<br>
I can go on endlessly.<br>
<br>
Why guilds die out in MMORPG's<br>
<br>
What kills a guild over time are things that destroy its membership base. Most of the time<br>
<br>
1. The game doesn't support casual gamers. Most veteran PvP guilds have grown up, gotten jobs, etc. They can still play, but not be level 50 in a month. They want to play and fight, but not spend 8 months leveling until they are good.<br>
<br>
2. Leveling treadmill games wasted hours of time numbing players into the same repetative monster killing over...and over...and over. The higher they get, the longer it takes, and eventually most people simply give up or quit.<br>
<br>
3. People get bored fighting for no cause, for no reason, no reward, no consequence, no bragging rights, no ability to impact the world.<br>
<br>
4. Nerf's, character changes, PvP inbalances, bugs, etc that force someone to reroll. Combine rerolling + leveling treadmill = cancelled account.<br>
<br>
5. Forced grouping to advance at anything better than a snail's pace. <br>
<br>
Rarely do players quit games because of PK's or PvP, but rather a combination of these factors I've mentioned thus far. Its far easier for development companies to blame it on PK's and PvP though.<br>
<br>
Final Thoughts<br>
<br>
Mythics game plan, leveling plan, Realm vs Realm plan, and risk/reward system are all incomplete. The result is 42% if their player base polled plays 21-40 hours a week and 24% play 11-20 hours per week. That's a lot of people who will find their way to level 30 within the first 65 days of the game only to find the game isn't complete with all the elements needed to support R vs R. That said, I think we all agree that its better to wait extra long for a game to come out that will actually be complete. Ala Shadowbane and its eternal wait.<br>
<br>
You have high levels in guilds complaining about the time it takes to level, the time it takes to travel, the lack of meaning for the post max(PvP) side of gameplay. The psychology of this and then with the high level players in a guild vanishing, quitting, etc puts strains on guilds. <br>
<br>
The human element is perhaps the most important element that keeps a PvP game alive. It kept oNWN alive and talked about for years. To keep the human element alive, you have to make sure the other things that turn fun into a job are removed from the game. Afterall its a game that people pay to enjoy, not pay to put in the hours of a part time job for 8 months before they can enjoy it.<br>
<br>
Epic clashes, guild interaction, bragging rights, is what its all about. The sooner people get there, the better it will be. The game stays fresh because there are always new jacks trying to be the next virtual king of the hill. If you make leveling very fast, your world is dynamic enough, resources mean something, and players can change the face of the world then you're truly promoting a new product instead of something that's been reshashed from old static concepts.<br>
<br>
While AC/EQ/DAOC have demonstrated success in sales and growing a customer base, there is a huge PvP base out there that is not satisfied with those three because they all have some or all of the things I've discussed. I can only hope that Shadowbane does not follow in their footsteps, have the same types of issues, and that it doesn't become a second job to play. <br>
<br>
To the game that gets it right goes the golden sword, and the rest shall be thrown to the carebears.<br>
